TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Social Cost of Carbon with Economic and Climate Risks
AU  - Cai, Yongyang
AU  - Lontzek, Thomas S.
Y1  - 2018/12/06
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701890
DO  - 10.1086/701890
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2684
EP  - 2734
VL  - 127
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Uncertainty about future economic and climate conditions substantially affects the choice of policies for managing interactions between the climate and the economy. We develop a framework of dynamic stochastic integration of climate and economy, and show that the social cost of carbon is substantially affected by both economic and climate risks and is a stochastic process with significant variation. We examine a wide but plausible range of values for critical parameters with robust results and show that large-scale computing makes it possible to analyze policies in models substantially more complex and realistic than usually used in the literature.
AB  - Uncertainty about future economic and climate conditions substantially affects the choice of policies for managing interactions between the climate and the economy. We develop a framework of dynamic stochastic integration of climate and economy, and show that the social cost of carbon is substantially affected by both economic and climate risks and is a stochastic process with significant variation. We examine a wide but plausible range of values for critical parameters with robust results and show that large-scale computing makes it possible to analyze policies in models substantially more complex and realistic than usually used in the literature.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701890
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701890
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Value of Flexible Work: Evidence from Uber Drivers
AU  - Chen, M. Keith
AU  - Chevalier, Judith A.
AU  - Rossi, Peter E.
AU  - Oehlsen, Emily
Y1  - 2018/12/13
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/702171
DO  - 10.1086/702171
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2735
EP  - 2794
VL  - 127
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Technology has facilitated new, nontraditional work arrangements, including the ride-sharing company Uber. Uber drivers provide rides anytime they choose. Using data on hourly earnings and driving, we document driver utilization of this real-time flexibility. We propose that the value of flexibility can be measured as deriving from time variation in the drivers? reservation wage. Measuring time variation in drivers? reservation wages allows us to estimate the surplus and labor supply implications of Uber relative to alternative, less-flexible work arrangements. Despite other drawbacks to the Uber arrangement, we estimate that Uber drivers earn more than twice the surplus they would in less-flexible arrangements.
AB  - Technology has facilitated new, nontraditional work arrangements, including the ride-sharing company Uber. Uber drivers provide rides anytime they choose. Using data on hourly earnings and driving, we document driver utilization of this real-time flexibility. We propose that the value of flexibility can be measured as deriving from time variation in the drivers? reservation wage. Measuring time variation in drivers? reservation wages allows us to estimate the surplus and labor supply implications of Uber relative to alternative, less-flexible work arrangements. Despite other drawbacks to the Uber arrangement, we estimate that Uber drivers earn more than twice the surplus they would in less-flexible arrangements.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/702171
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/702171
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Educational Assortative Mating and Household Income Inequality
AU  - Eika, Lasse
AU  - Mogstad, Magne
AU  - Zafar, Basit
Y1  - 2018/12/12
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/702018
DO  - 10.1086/702018
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2795
EP  - 2835
VL  - 127
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We use data from Denmark, Germany, Norway, the United Kingdom, and the United States to document the degree of educational assortative mating, how it evolves over time, and the extent to which it differs between countries. This descriptive analysis motivates and guides a decomposition analysis in which we quantify the contribution of various factors to the distribution of household income. We find that assortative mating accounts for a nonnegligible part of the cross-sectional inequality in household income in each country. However, changes in assortative mating over time barely move the time trends in household income inequality.
AB  - We use data from Denmark, Germany, Norway, the United Kingdom, and the United States to document the degree of educational assortative mating, how it evolves over time, and the extent to which it differs between countries. This descriptive analysis motivates and guides a decomposition analysis in which we quantify the contribution of various factors to the distribution of household income. We find that assortative mating accounts for a nonnegligible part of the cross-sectional inequality in household income in each country. However, changes in assortative mating over time barely move the time trends in household income inequality.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/702018
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/702018
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Value of Medicaid: Interpreting Results from the Oregon Health Insurance Experiment
AU  - Finkelstein, Amy
AU  - Hendren, Nathaniel
AU  - Luttmer, Erzo F. P.
Y1  - 2018/12/17
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/702238
DO  - 10.1086/702238
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2836
EP  - 2874
VL  - 127
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We develop frameworks for welfare analysis of Medicaid and apply them to the Oregon Health Insurance Experiment. Across different approaches, we estimate low-income uninsured adults? willingness to pay for Medicaid between $0.5 and $1.2 per dollar of the resource cost of providing Medicaid; estimates of the expected transfer Medicaid provides to recipients are relatively stable across approaches, but estimates of its additional value from risk protection are more variable. We also estimate that the resource cost of providing Medicaid to an additional recipient is only 40 percent of Medicaid?s total cost; 60 percent of Medicaid spending is a transfer to providers of uncompensated care for the low-income uninsured.
AB  - We develop frameworks for welfare analysis of Medicaid and apply them to the Oregon Health Insurance Experiment. Across different approaches, we estimate low-income uninsured adults? willingness to pay for Medicaid between $0.5 and $1.2 per dollar of the resource cost of providing Medicaid; estimates of the expected transfer Medicaid provides to recipients are relatively stable across approaches, but estimates of its additional value from risk protection are more variable. We also estimate that the resource cost of providing Medicaid to an additional recipient is only 40 percent of Medicaid?s total cost; 60 percent of Medicaid spending is a transfer to providers of uncompensated care for the low-income uninsured.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/702238
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/702238
Y2  - 2024/03/20
